---
title: "Information to Knowledge"
output:
  html_document: 
    keep_md: yes
---



Lawrence Tomaziefski, 13 September 2020

Berengueres et al. start Chapter 2 of their book Introduction to Data Visualization & Story Telling by stating, “The foundation of a useful chart is seldom graphic design (2019).”  Useful charts or visualizations effectively translate information to knowledge through simplicity, thoughtful use of color, and balancing information with meaning (Berengueres, Fenwick, & Sandell, 2019).  This report explores these key ideas with visualizations built using The Drug Consumption Dataset (Fehrman, Mirkes, Muhammad, Egan, & Gorban, Drug Consumption (Quantified) Dataset).  Additionally, insights into what knowledge is gained from each visualization is highlighted.    

The research team of Ferhman et. al collected the data for The Drug Consumption Dataset, and the dataset is found on the University of California-Irvine’s Machine Learning Repository (Fehrman, Mirkes, Muhammad, Egan, & Gorban, Drug Consumption (Quantified) Dataset).   The dataset contains the responses of 1,885 adults to an online survey for the purpose of exploring the interaction of personality attributes and drug consumption risk.  The Drug Consumption Dataset consists of 29 variables divided into three components; demographics, personality measures, and reported use of legal substances (e.g. alcohol) and illicit substance (e.g. heroin) use (Fehrman, Mirkes, Muhammad, Egan, and Gorban, Drug Consumption (Quantified) Dataset, 2016).  

As a disclaimer, the author of this report used this dataset to support previous analysis.  Therefore, the author took several steps were taken to ensure that the dataset is suitable for statistical or data mining techniques during data processing and exploratory data analysis.  With that the data is adequately prepared to support the creation of useful visualizations aimed at answering three questions: 

* What substances are used more than others, 

* Does gender play a role in what types of substances are used, and

*	What is the interaction between personality and substance use?

Logically when exploring The Drug Consumption Dataset, a natural first question that is what types of substances did respondents report use more?  The bubble plot below highlights the number of and percentage respondents that reported using each substance.  The visualization uses size and color to compare the magnitudes of substance use.

What is the story that is emerging from this visualization? Not surprisingly alcohol is the most prevalent substance used by far.  Depending on how you interpret this visualization, two to three other grouping of substances appear here as well.  In the second grouping of substances, nicotine and cannabis appear to have a special relationship with equal reported use.  Correlation analysis can help with the determination of if a statistically significant relationship does exist.

At the lower end of the scale are the majority of the illicit substances, and one may ask why reported use of these substances so low?  Is this because of the negative social connotations associated with these types of substances?  Social desirability occurs when respondents answer in a way that align with perceived social norms; even if responding anonymously.  In this case due to the negativity associated with crack usage, admitting to using crack is much different that admitting to smoking pot.  The alternative is that answer that these illicit substances are just less widely used.  The implications of this potential bias is not the focus of this report, but an example of how data visualization can highlight such issues.  
Berengueres et al. urge limiting the amount of information being conveyed in a single visualization (2019).  The visualization in Figure 1 has redundant layers conveying the same information.  Figure 2 below is minimalist approach the visualization; count of reported users was left out in favor focusing on just percentage of the population.  Using this approach, the stratification is harder to pick up on, but the main ideas are still relayed.

The next question explored is does gender play a role in what types of substances are used?  Before exploring this question using data visualization, Berengueres et al. urge that there are considerations that needed to be made before making “human-centric” charts (2019).  The developer’s inherent bias towards minority or vulnerable populations may manifest itself either unintentionally or not.  It is good practice to ensure that visualizations are checked to ensure that cognitive biases do not manifest themselves (Berengueres, Fenwick, & Sandell, 2019).  When creating a visualization that deals with genders, one tendency may be to use blue and pink to distinguish between males and females. Although innocent enough, these colors carry certain connotations and be offensive to some.  Therefore, colors that elicit these types responses should be avoided (Berengueres, Fenwick, & Sandell, 2019).  For this reason, Figure 3 below uses greyscale to highlight the difference in genders.  Avoiding issues that distract from the meaning conveyed allows the audience to focus on interpretation of the graph.

Getting back to the question at hand, gender does play a role in reporting of substances and in the types of substances used.  Note that the sample population is made up of half males and half females, mirroring the general population quite nicely.  Males and females reported the use of alcohol, cannabis, and nicotine at roughly the same rate as females.  Beyond that the graph is skewed more heavily towards males, with males reporting substance use two to three times more than females in some cases.  Why is this the case?  Potentially, males are less risk averse leading them using illicit substances at a higher rate than females.  This visualization provides the knowledge that a disparity exists and a starting point for asking follow-on questions.   

The last question this report explores is a bit more focused than the previous two questions: Can a person can be categorized as a heroin user based on personality?  During the exploratory data analysis phase of analysis, a researcher may produce a boxplot like the one in Figure 4 below.  Although very rich in information, the visualization surpasses the point that Berengueres et. al (2019) describe as the sweet spot between information and meaning and is overloaded.

The boxplot is not all bad, as a lot of useful information is being conveyed.  First, there are clear differences within personality measures between respondents who reported using heroin and those that did not. Second, the boxplot confirms the existence of outliers and where they lie.  Finally, there appears to be a difference between personality measures.  Again, the visualization is information rich, but uses fourteen different plots and seven colors.  Hard for normal people to comprehend and synthesize efficiently.  

According to the principles of keeping visualizations simple and limiting the use of color, the density plots in Figure 5 below are a better approach.  The same information is conveyed much more efficiently with the use of seven individual plots and two colors.  Whereas the boxplots were useful for exploratory data analysis but probably would not be presented to a larger group, the density plots are presentation ready.

The intent of this report was to demonstrate how useful visualizations effectively translate information to knowledge through simplicity, thoughtful use of color, and balancing meaning.  Each of the visualizations in this report were focused on answering a single question and relayed a limited amount of information.  It is tempting to think that effective visualizations tell the whole story, but effective visualizations highlight areas of knowledge that must be synthesized with other pieces of information to complete the transformation from data to wisdom (Berengueres, Fenwick, & Sandell, 2019).  Going forward keep this in mind, effective visualizations support analysis and are not a substitute for analysis.
